		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Howard Zinn</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<table class="infobox biography vcard vevent" cellspacing="5" style="width: 22em; text-align: left; font-size: 88%; line-height: 1.5em; width:22em; font-size:95%; text-align:left;">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" class="fn summary" style="text-align:center; font-size: 125%; font-weight: bold; text-align:center; font-size:125%;"><b>Howard Zinn</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" class="" style="text-align:center; padding:4pt; line-height:1.25em; text-align:center; font-size:8pt;"><a href="/wiki/File:Howard_Zinn.jpg" class="image" title="Howard Zinn.jpg"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Howard_Zinn.jpg/225px-Howard_Zinn.jpg" width="225" height="169" border="0" /></a><br />
<div style="padding-top:2pt;"><span style="">Howard Zinn Speaking at <a href="/wiki/Marlboro_College" title="Marlboro College">Marlboro College</a> Feb. 2004</span></div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th style="padding:0.2em 1.0em 0.2em 0.2em; background:transparent; line-height:1.2em; text-align:left; font-size:90%;">Born</th>
<td class="" style="padding:0.2em; line-height:1.3em; vertical-align:middle; font-size:90%;">August 24, 1922 <span style="display:none">(<span class="bday">1922-08-24</span>)</span> <span class="noprint">(age&#160;86)</span><br />
Brooklyn, New York</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th style="padding:0.2em 1.0em 0.2em 0.2em; background:transparent; line-height:1.2em; text-align:left; font-size:90%;">Occupation</th>
<td class="role" style="padding:0.2em; line-height:1.3em; vertical-align:middle; font-size:90%;"><a href="/wiki/Professor" title="Professor">Professor</a>, <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">Historian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Playwright" title="Playwright">Playwright</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th style="padding:0.2em 1.0em 0.2em 0.2em; background:transparent; line-height:1.2em; text-align:left; font-size:90%;">Spouse(s)</th>
<td class="" style="padding:0.2em; line-height:1.3em; vertical-align:middle; font-size:90%;">Roslyn Zinn</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Howard Zinn</b> (born August 24, 1922) is a <a href="/wiki/Professor" title="Professor">professor</a>, <a href="/wiki/Political_science" title="Political science">political scientist</a>, <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">historian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Social_criticism" title="Social criticism">social critic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Socialist" title="Socialist" class="mw-redirect">socialist</a>, activist and <a href="/wiki/Playwright" title="Playwright">playwright</a>, best known as author of the <a href="/wiki/Bestseller" title="Bestseller">bestseller</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/A_People%27s_History_of_the_United_States" title="A People's History of the United States">A People's History of the United States</a></i>.</p>
<p>Zinn has been active in the movements for <a href="/wiki/African-American_Civil_Rights_Movement_(1955-1968)" title="African-American Civil Rights Movement (1955-1968)" class="mw-redirect">Civil Rights</a>, <a href="/wiki/Civil_Liberties" title="Civil Liberties" class="mw-redirect">Civil Liberties</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Peace_movement" title="Peace movement">anti-war movements</a> in the United States.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> He has written extensively on all three subjects.</p>
<p>The author of some 20 books, Zinn is Professor Emeritus in the Political Science Department at <a href="/wiki/Boston_University" title="Boston University">Boston University</a>. He lives in the <a href="/wiki/Auburndale,_Massachusetts" title="Auburndale, Massachusetts">Auburndale</a> neighborhood of <a href="/wiki/Newton,_Massachusetts" title="Newton, Massachusetts">Newton, Massachusetts</a>. His late wife of 64 years, Roslyn Zinn, died<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> on May 14, 2008 at their home. An artist and editor, Roslyn had a role in editing all of Zinn's books and many of his articles.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> Zinn has two children, Myla and Jeff, and five grandchildren.</p>
